as a safety concern I just wanna point out you have to really be careful when using a product outside it's intended to use to dupe another product. and duping a product is a bit more complicated than just looking at the first few ingredients *listed like 70% isopropyl alcohol is not a dupe for setting spray. for one there are two different types of alcohol. rubbing alcohol is isopropyl alcohol and alcohol in setting sprays is usually the type we drink just denatured it a little bit so you don't drink it but it's also not the first ingredient and not the only ingredient because it's not the alcohol itself that sets your makeup. the alcohol is just a carrier or solvent for the actual ingredients that set the makeup called fixatives. As the alcohol evaporates, the fixative forms a film on the face to lock makeup into place same way Hairspray works. That’s why Hairspray is an affordable dupe for setting sprays. another example would be using Gorilla Snot as a eyeshadow. Just because a product is safe for one area of the body, doesn't mean it's safe for all areas of the body because beyond shampoos, hair products typically are not tested to be eye safe, so just be careful when using some of these dupes.

you need to throw these away immediately if you are using makeup wipes to take off your makeup you need to stop hi miss guuuurrrrllll I also am not a huge fan of makeup wipes but not for the majority of the reasons that you listed because a lot of them are very much wrong my name is Ava Perkins I'm a cosmetic chemist I agree to the fact that makeup wipes don't do the best job of cleansing your skin but the claims that it's going to disrupt your acid mantle or change your pH or um be really stripping because they contain alcohol or they create micro tears on your skin those things are wrong so let's start off with the acid mantle claim which also relates to pH what is the acid mantle the acid mantle is essentially a mixture of sebum and sweat and dead skin cells and water and lactic acid fatty acids all the good things and this basically creates some sort of like protective layer of your skin when you compromise the acid mantle you are basically kind of compromising your skin's barrier as well however I don't agree with the claims that makeup wipes are going to do this because the cleansing ingredients that are in makeup wipes are not harsh really at all the thing with like old fashioned soaps like that were used decades ago is that they had a really high pH and that could definitely do a little bit of damage to your skin but nowadays cleansers not even just makeup wipes but cleansers in general they're formulated to a pH that is very similar to your skin's pH but despite all the pH talk what really matters more is the harshness of the cleansing ingredients that you're using or just the harshness of the formulation itself and how do you know if your cleanser did too much well it's actually that stripped down feeling if your skin feels really tight and squeaky clean after you're done cleansing that is actually not a good sign that means you overdid it it doesn't entirely come from pH it can but like I said a lot of products today are not formulated how they were decades ago with a higher pH like that as far as micro tears I totally thought that was a thing too a few years ago until I was kindly called out by dermatologist that that is not a thing um and I tried to look up you know pictures of micro tears under the microscope like you had said I was not able to find anything to my knowledge I do not think that micro tears exist and as far as alcohol being uh an ingredient in makeup wipes they're not at least the ones that I've seen that are popular if you look at the ingredient list alcohol is not in there at all and so therefore won't be stripping to your skin listen like I said I don't think that makeup wipes are the best option for removing makeup or cleansing your face but sometimes they're the most feasible especially if you're coming back from a late night or if you know it's just too mentally draining to wash your face makeup wipes are much better than nothing but they're also not the best for the environment either so those are things to just consider but continue to live your life if you enjoy using makeup wipes who am I to stop you they're fine to use but just maybe not the best option okay goodbye

I saw you went to prom, love that for you, you look like you had a great time and you looked great. um if you are still wanting to like learn how to work with your hooded eyelids, I would like to offer some tips as someone who thought for the longest time they had hooded eyelids, um but I've also done makeup on a lot of my friends who happen to have hooded eyelids as well. um also feel free to ignore this, do whatever you like. so one, you're gonna give yourself a higher crease. the easiest way that I find to do this is I'll put a dot of primer kinda in the center of my lid about like right here and I'll look up, like just roll my eyes up to the ceiling, and then when I look back in the mirror straight ahead, um wherever that dot goes, like however far it's reached, I make sure to draw whatever I'm trying to show over it, so that will be my new crease area. two,  I try to keep my eyeliner thinner. since you gave yourself more space by creating that fake crease, you don't wanna take it away by giving yourself a thicker liner, unless that's whatever look you're going for, like please do whatever you feel. voice_to_text: You can only do silicone and silicone or you can only do water based with water based are completely wrong. I try to tell people this all the time. Whoever started this whole water based water based silicone silicone is like the biggest marketing scheme that's currently happening in like the makeup community. Number one. Most of your products have both water and silicone in it anyways, so if it can't mix on your face, why can't it mix in the product and be okay? Also, if you're moisturizing or using sunscreen, it's probably water based too, not silicone based. So why can you put silicone primer and foundation on that and it doesn't peel? Why does it only matter for the primer and the foundation if you find something spilling on your face? There could be a million different reasons why, but I'll usually take all my makeup off and exfoliate my face and then reapply my skincare and it'll end up looking fine for the most part. I use water based primer and silicone in this and foundation and it looks good. So moral of the story just don't believe everything you see on TikTok and don't fall into schemes where now you feel like you have to label all of your different products or go out and buy different one.
